ce:section.ce:para:
Photodynamic Therapy (PDT) has been considered an alternative cancer treatment based on the synergistic action of three components: photosensitizer (PS), light, and oxygen (Fig. 3
                        ). PS is localized in the tumor lesion and excited with light at an appropriate wavelength in order to produce Reactive Oxygen Species (ROS) through photophysical and photochemical processes. ROS such as hydroxyl radical (OH∙), peroxyl radicals (ROO∙), superoxide radical (O2
                        ∙-), hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) and singlet oxygen (1O2) lead to the death of cancer cells via the initiation of cellular death pathways and finally to tumor destruction [8,18–20].

Another research was based on the existence of quinoline groups in nucleic acid probes in order to synthesize CDs capable of nucleic acid targeting using quinoline derivatives (I-CDs). CDs were further linked with folic acid (I-CDs@FA) to boost PS's selectivity. In vivo research was carried out in 4T1 tumor-bearing mice under various therapeutic schemes: LED light only (700 nm, 70 mW/cm2, 30 min), PS only (I-CDs, 5 mg/kg), PDT (I-CDs + light), PS only (I-CDs@FA, 5 mg/kg), and PDT (I-CDs@FA + light) with an optimal drug-to-light interval of 20 h. The modification of PS with folic acid was of the utmost importance, as this type of PS achieved higher tumor reduction (Fig. 45
                           ). The observation of mice's weight for a determined time interval after treatment and the lack of damage to major organs highlighted the safety of the PS. Fluorescent nature of the produced CDs allowed the monitoring of CDs' localization and biodistribution in vivo. Specially, CDs were accumulated stably in tumor site for up to 72 h and were localized in liver and kidney, proving their successful metabolism (Fig. 46
                           ) [168].

Another case refers to the use of CDs in PDT combined with chemotherapy. Specially, CDs were modified with metformin (Met), bovine serum albumin (BSA), and HA to increase tumor oxygenation, biocompatibility, and selectivity, respectively (Fig. 49
                           ). In vivo studies were carried out in sarcoma (S180)-bearing mice and the optimum therapeutic scheme was the use of DOX/Met/BSA-HA-CDs in PDT in combination with chemotherapy. It must be mentioned that the PS is not toxic in comparison with free DOX based on the control of mice's weight [174]. Furthermore, CDs have been applied as PSs in combined PDT/catalytic therapy upon conjugation with dendritic mesoporous silica nanoparticles (DMSNs), platinum nanoparticles (Pt NPs), and HA. The role of HA is to increase cancer selectivity via its interaction with the overexpressed CD44 receptors in tumor cells, while the Pt NPs are involved in the catalytic therapy. Taking into account the POD-, OXD-, and CAT-mimicking activities of Pt NPs, these NPs can produce OH∙ and O2
                           ∙- and produce oxygen via the detection and decomposition of H2O2. The proposed PS (HA-PCD) was examined in combined PDT/catalytic therapy in 4T1 tumor-bearing mice irradiated at 635 nm with a fluence rate of 200 mW/cm2 for 10 min, resulting in the optimum tumor suppression. In the case of independent PDT (cells incubation with HA-CDs-laser irradiation), improved tumor destruction was observed in comparison with the catalytic therapy (cells incubation with HA-PCDs-without laser irradiation), but tumor growth in the final stages of PDT was shown as a result of the inability to maintain the ROS production rate. Furthermore, HA-PCDs could retain in mice 48 h post injection based on fluorescence imaging [175].

The research of Yang et al. presented the use of a nanoplatform based on GDs for repeated PDT and prolongation of PS retention in tumors (Fig. 50
                           ). GDs have a dual role, acting as carrier for the effective delivery of the porphyrin derivative tetracarboxylphenyl porphyrin (TCPP) and exhibiting a mild photothermal effect that reinforces PS's cellular uptake. The PS TCPP-GDs were further linked with RGD peptide to increase selectivity to cells expressing ανβ3 integrin. In vivo studies were conducted in A549 tumor-bearing mice, and the PS was effective in reducing tumor growth. The PDT was repeated after 6 days, and total tumor elimination was shown in this group. The prolonged retention of PS in the tumor area facilitates the application of repeated PDT, which aims to increase tumor reduction. Specially, fluorescence imaging revealed maximum fluorescence signal of the PS at the tumor location at 24 h, while PS's fluorescence was evident even after 96 h post injection (Fig. 51
                           ). However, repeated PDT may cause side effects due to the high dose of PSs, so it is vital for the PS to be efficient in low doses (3.5 μmol/kg) [176].

Carbon-based nanomaterials, including fullerenes, carbon nanotubes, graphene oxide, and carbon-based dots, have been extensively used in PDT to treat various types of cancer up to date (Fig. 52
                     ). Research studies highlight some important properties of the above nanostructures and some restrictions regarding their usage in PDT, which are summarized in Table 1
                     . The knowledge of both features and limitations could be a valuable tool in future studies in order to develop synthetic protocols for PSs with improved hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, tumor selectivity, and ROS generation ability.
